08808nam a22011295i 9781501508844DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182002gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97815015088447 a10.1515/97815015088442doi  a(DE-B1597)493221  a(OCoLC)1083622962  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aQD181.B4 7aSCI0480002bisacsh04a546.39122300aBeryllium :bMineralogy, Petrology, and Geochemistry /ced. by Edward S. Grew. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (XII, 691 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReviews in Mineralogy & Geochemistry ,x1529-6466 ;v5000tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD/ COVER -- tTable of Contents -- t1. Mineralogy, Petrology and Geochemistry of Beryllium: An Introduction and List of Beryllium Minerals -- t2. Behavior of Beryllium During Solar System and Planetary Evolution: Evidence from Planetary Materials -- t3. Trace-Element Systematics of Beryllium in Terrestrial Materials -- t4. Rates and Timing of Earth Surface Processes From In Situ-Produced Cosmogenic Be-10 -- t5. Cosmogenic Be-10 and the Solid Earth: Studies in Geomagnetism, Subduction Zone Processes, and Active Tectonics -- t6. Environmental Chemistry of Beryllium-7 -- t7. Environmental Chemistry of Beryllium -- t8. Beryllium Analyses by Secondary Ion Mass Spectrometry -- t9. The Crystal Chemistry of Beryllium -- t10. Mineralogy of Beryllium in Granitic Pegmatites -- t11. Beryllium in Silicic Magmas and the Origin of Beryl-Bearing Pegmatites -- t12. Beryllium in Metamorphic Environments (emphasis on aluminous compositions) -- t13. Be-Minerals: Synthesis, Stability, and Occurrence in Metamorphic Rocks -- t14. Non-pegmatitic Deposits of Beryllium: Mineralogy, Geology, Phase Equilibria and Origin0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVolume 50 of Reviews in Mineralogy and Geochemistry treats Beryllium and its cosmogenic isotopes. This volume includes an overview of Be studies in the earth sciences and a systematic classification of Be minerals based on their crystal structure. It treats the analysis of these minerals by the secondary ion mass spectroscopy as well as experimental studies of systems involving Be. Moreover, this volume reviews the behavior of Be in the Solar System, with an emphasis on meteorites, the Moon and Mars, and the implications of this behavior for the evolution of the solar system. It gives an overview of the terrestrial geochemistry of Be and discusses the contamination of the environment by this anthropogenic toxin. It reports use of the longer lived Be-10 to assess erosion rates and other surficial processes and how this isotope can yield independent temporal records of geomagnetic field variations for comparison with records obtained by measuring natural remnant magnetization, be a chemical tracer for processes in convergent margins, and can date events in Cenozoic tectonics. It reviews applications of the shorter lived isotope Be-7 in environmental studies as well. Residual phases include acidic plutonic and volcanic rocks, whose geochemistry and evolution are covered, while granitic pegmatites, which are well-known for their remarkable, if localized, Be enrichments and a wide variety of Be mineral assemblages, are reviewed. Not all Be concentrations have obvious magmatic affinities; for example, one class of emerald deposits results from Be being introduced by heated brines. Pelitic rocks are an important reservoir of Be in the Earth's crust and their metamorphism plays a critical role in recycling of Be in subduction zones, eventually, anatectic processes complete the cycle, providing a source of Be for granitic rocks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBeryllium. 4aAufsatzsammlu